	(532,10,'2015-10-08 08:15:41','2015-10-08 08:15:41','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_single_image image=\"541\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_large=\"\" img_link_target=\"_self\" img_size=\"full\" alignment=\"center\"][vc_column_text]Nick Martin sits on the beach in <a href=\"http://www.theartofslowtravel.com/2012/01/seminyak-beach-bali/\" target=\"_blank\">Seminyak</a>, Bali. The surfers are out, cutting up the waves, and Nick watches from the shade with a cold bottle of beer in his hand. As Nick enjoys the scenery and chats with his girlfriend, a push notification comes to his tablet. It seems he forgot to turn off the Zopim app before he left the office. In Nick\'s case, the office is a three-story villa in Ubud, with a pool that overlooks a serene Indonesian rice field. It\'s also only a 20-minute drive from Seminyak. Nick takes the first sip of his beer, and picks up the tablet. The message is from a potential client, and after a few brief exchanges, Nick gets another push notification from his collaborative teamwork app that informs him the lead is now a paying customer. Nick smiles for a moment, then turns his attention back to his girlfriend.\n\nThat was really a wow moment for me,\" Nick recalls fondly. I was in Seminyak, enjoying myself on the beach, then I had this crazy out-of-nowhere chat which resulted in a big sale just 15 minutes later.\" He thinks for a minute before recounting another similar moment. Nick and his staff were sitting at a beach club in Sanur, on the western side of Bali, and he realised he was able to handle his accounting via tablet. So it was kind of funny, I looked around, and I was just sitting there at this really fun beach club. I thought, <em>yeah okay, I just did my finances. It\'s all done. It\'s all aligned</em>.\"\n\nSo what does Nick Martin do for a living, and how can he run a business from the beach in Indonesia? Nick is the founder and CEO of a digital startup called <a href=\"http://www.magloft.com/\" target=\"_blank\">MagLoft</a>, an online software-as-a-service firm that helps independent publishers create fully branded magazines on iOS and Android, or formatted for any other web platform. I\'m definitely able to work on MagLoft and the business from anywhere, which is very, very awesome,\" says Nick with a satisfied grin. My true goal in life has always been to have the ability to choose when and where I work. While MagLoft is based in Bali and won\'t necessarily relocate, having had that dream from the early days, it kind of makes me a digital nomad by heart.\"[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row css=\".vc_custom_1444286983273{padding-top: 10px !important;padding-bottom: 10px !important;background-position: center !important;background-repeat: no-repeat !important;background-size: cover !important;}\"][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_single_image image=\"543\" alignment=\"center\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_large=\"\" img_link_target=\"_self\" img_size=\"full\"][vc_column_text]Today, with his blonde hair and blue eyes, his stellar tan, and his apparent lifestyle, Nick looks for all the world like the typical beach bum: the kind of guy who spends his days surfing and his nights playing guitar with friends around a campfire. You might not peg him as the e-business type  until you get him talking, that is. But just five years ago, Nick\'s life was a very different story. There\'s no beach in this part of the tale.\n\nAfter attending Copenhagen Business School, double-majoring in economics and computer science to graduate as computer game designer, the half-Danish half-English 20-something went straight to work at a local bank. He sat in a cubicle, crunching numbers as a retail analyst. Nick says he wasn\'t unhappy working there, but deep down he was searching for the kind of freedom that most of us only dream of as we gaze out the window and wait for the clock to strike 5 pm.\n\nDon\'t get me wrong, it was a great job, with amazing people. I had the big salary, a ton of benefits, my own car, a nice big flat  those things were all there,\" he explains. But at the end of the day, I just knew that the nine-to-five wasn\'t for me. Although I was having a great time, I knew that wasn\'t my future.\"[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_single_image image=\"545\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_large=\"\" img_link_target=\"_self\" img_size=\"full\" alignment=\"center\"][vc_column_text]At the time, in an effort to stay stimulated, Nick was dabbling with a few online company ideas in addition to his day job. A friend of his knew he was interested in tech startups, and introduced him to a program called <a href=\"http://www.projectgetaway.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Project Getaway</a>. It was a 30-day event in Bali where entrepreneurs get to meet and build startups together,\" he says. They get to live together and work together. While everyone is working on different companies, they all get to be with like-minded people, share ideas, and have the experience together.\"\n\nNick was unable to contain his excitement. He immediately reached out to the founder of Project Getaway, a fellow Danish serial entrepreneur and investor named Michael Bodekaer. When the two realized how closely their visions synced up, Nick and Bodekaer were on the next flight to Bali, and Nick\'s life  complete with nine-to-five at the bank  would never be the same.\n\nToday, along with running MagLoft full-time, Nick is also one of the senior managers of <a href=\"http://liv.it/\" target=\"_blank\">Liv.it</a>, the firm responsible for Project Getaway. Liv.it consists of nine villas in the artsy Balinese town of <a href=\"http://www.indonesia.travel/en/destination/277/ubud\" target=\"_blank\">Ubud</a>. The houses serve as accommodation and workspaces for the entrepreneurs in-residence. The firm has five full-time staff members handling the cooking and cleaning. This way, Nick says, the people who come can focus solely on building their online businesses in paradise. Nick often steps out onto his terrace with a morning coffee, only to look down and see tech founders lounging by the pool, writing code on their laptops.\n\nNick launched MagLoft in mid-2013, and claims the business has seen steady revenue growth month-on-month since its inception. It has started to pull in high-profile partners, one of which is Yahoo. MagLoft has also received some investor interest, but Nick confirms he\'d prefer to let his business grow organically for now. As such, he invites techies to submit their resumes, as MagLoft prepares for a hiring spree.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_single_image image=\"540\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_large=\"\" img_link_target=\"_self\" img_size=\"full\"][vc_column_text]I\'m really proud to be building a solid business slowly rather than racing around like crazy trying to find the next <a href=\"http://fortune.com/2015/01/22/the-age-of-unicorns/\" target=\"_blank\">unicorn</a>,\" Nick explains. For me, I feel the startup industry can be a crazy ride if you live in a big city, with investors telling you one thing and advisers telling you another  there\'s always this massive hype.\" In Nick\'s opinion, it\'s precisely this hype that creates a stressful life for entrepreneurs: indeed, creating the antithesis of building a business on one\'s own terms.\n\nToday, Nick\'s remote business lifestyle is possible because of three key mobile apps that let him run MagLoft from a tablet anywhere in the world: <a href=\"https://slack.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Slack</a>, <a href=\"https://www.xero.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Xero</a>, and <a href=\"https://www.zopim.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Zopim</a>. Slack helps him direct and communicate with his team of web developers and business reps, while Xero lets him handle the accounting from anywhere. Meanwhile, Zopim lets him speak directly to his customers. In terms of efficiency, Nick says these three apps are crucial in allowing him to jump in at any stage of the business cycle. The fact that they\'re all compatible with his tablet is an added bonus in terms of location independence.\n\nWhen asked what advice he has for aspiring entrepreneurs looking out the window still daydreaming, he says, You invest so much time in your job, eight to nine hours per day. If it\'s not something you\'re excited about doing, then it\'s really not optimal. Take risks and enjoy the ride while it lasts. Just do it, and if everything fails, then there\'s always the option to get a job, work a little bit, save up some money and try again.\"[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/1\"][vc_single_image image=\"539\" alignment=\"center\" border_color=\"grey\" img_link_large=\"\" img_link_target=\"_self\" img_size=\"full\"][vc_column_text]Nick is grateful that technology can allow him to pursue his dream in paradise while also achieving a work-life balance. While he devotes a lot of time to MagLoft, he also believes working in Bali is about freedom above all else. Leaving his poolside office and working from the beach with a tablet is a liberty Nick often takes.\n\nHe adds, After five years at the bank, it just got very repetitive, and I decided it was time to do something radical about it. Today, I live a very modest life in Bali. It\'s dynamic, it\'s exciting, it\'s challenging, it\'s an emotional roller coaster  but I\'ve never been happier.\"\n\nNaturally. Nick is living life now on his terms.\n\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Building a Business on Your Own Terms','','publish','open','open','','building-a-business-on-your-own-terms','','','2015-10-08 08:15:41','2015-10-08 08:15:41','',0,'http://asus-zenpad.stagingapps.net/?p=532',0,'post','',0),
